UML:TaggedValue.value: The AreaHierarchy (AH) package contains common behavior model for any nested hierarchy of areas. The model addresses issues of navigation and cross referencing between hierarchies and the scoping of topology to versions of hierarchies. The hierarchy describes the topological relationships, not the (potentially multiple) alternative geometric descriptions of objects (see package AreaRepresentation).

-- Definition -- The UD sub-package contains logical definition and common behavior for any nested hierarchy of units The model addresses issues of navigation and cross referencing between hierarchies and the scoping of topology to versions of hierarchies. UD describes the topological relationships, not the (potentially multiple) alternative geometric descriptions of objects (see package AD / AR).

-- Definition -- VersionDefinition relates to the area model entities, which are defined by the definition process, e.g., transaction processes related to these model entities such as creation, change, deletion etc. The VersionDefinition can be seen as a common model of metadata to support tracing object definition and source of normative geometry representation where relevant.

-- Definition -- The GeometryRepresentation is the geographical representation of any recorded (versioned) topological unit. This model provides for multiple geometry representations of an area object independent of its definition, i.e., while a jurisdictional entity remains unchanged (to ensure its spatial relationship with other units), its geographical representation may change over.
A vocabulary for terms that name the level in a hierarchy

-- Definition -- The GeometryRepresentation is the geographical representation of any recorded (versioned) topological unit. This model provides for multiple geometry representations of an area object independent of its definition, i.e., while a jurisdictional entity remains unchanged (to ensure its spatial relationship with other units), its geographical representation may change over.
MaritimeUnits overlap, e.g., CS subsumes EEZ whereas CZ is subsumed by EEZ and CS

-- Definition -- The geometry definition feature refers to the geometrical data of the geometry of a defined unit.
Using ISO 19125 (Simple Feature Geometry), an area representation is described by a 'MultiSurface' object, which represents a collection of one or more polygons. each polygon is described by a collection of 'Curves', e.g., a 'LinearRing' describing a polygon..
-- ISO 19125 vs ISO 19107-- Individual SF geometry types correspond to one or more geometry types of spatial schema, e.g., SF geometry collection (e.g., MultiSurface) corresponds to the GM_Aggregate of the spatial schema.
A URI identifier for the feature. In GML this would be instantiated as gml:identifier

Examples: adjacent: State NSW borders State QLD contains: State NSW contains City Sydney intersects: Commonwealth Electoral Unit intersects State Electoral Unit disjoint: State NSW is disjoint to State WA

-- Definition -- A unit is defined as a logical entity (stand-alone or part of an hierarchy of entities) used across various themes and sub-themes/datasets. It describes the generic information and behavior shared across all entities of the data foundation, e.g., name/object identifier (e.g., using gml:name and gml:identifier) and hierarchical topology respectively.
-- Definition -- Generic administrative unit feature type. -- Note -- This covers administrative unit types that are not modeled in a more specialized schema.
In many cases these relate to a specific administrative or service function, as delegated by the relevant government unit. These include - catchment management authorities - school zones - police districts - fire and emergency service areas - cadastral units (county, district, parish, hundred, division)
In other cases, the unit, through formally gazetted, is primarily ceremonial or informative with few or no administrative functions, such as - city, metropolitan area - locality, suburb
Administrative units generally do not intersect or overlap for a particular function or service within the scope of the government unit that authorizes it.
There is a relationship with the government unit that is responsible for delegating the specific function, and there may be relationships with other administrative units.

A description of the unit. This may be textual description such as the gazetted description of the polygon or more general description, such as "rural Victorian electorate". Will be instantiated in GML as gml:description.

-- Definition -- An unit hierarchical refers to the overall hierarchy of units (represents the entire hierarchy).

-- Definition -- An hierarchical unit extends the unit definition with an hierarchal structure describing the topology of units (represents an individual element of that hierarchy).
In general, the root element starts with 'level=1' and has no higher units (meaning it is the parent) but possibly lower level units at 'level = 1 +n'.
In reverse, a leaf element has 'level=maxLevel' with has no more lower units (as it is the leaf) but possibly higher level units with 'level=maxLevel-n'.
